    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-09-22T08:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-09-22T08:30:00-05:00" n="872"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d872">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">833.5151/543: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reed</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-09-22T10:00:00-03:30"
                            >September 22, 1938—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 22—9:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>76. According to the Bank of the Republic import quotas of controlled foreign
                    exchange for the month of September have just been granted to 12 countries
                    excluding the United States. Quotas total 497,000 pounds of which 160,000 are
                    for Great Britain and 120,000 for Germany. The bank advises that there is a
                    balance available from the free exchange quota of 280,000 dollars previously
                    granted to the United States for agricultural machinery and urges importers to
                    submit applications therefor.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reed</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
